Please give us a call at 701-642-8585 Copyright © • Wick Communications Terms of Use | Privacy Policy Jackson Allard, left, is fighting for his life after a series of lung-related health issues. Jackson is seen with his mom, Jaime Foertsch. Editor’s Note: By the request of our readers, and with permission from WDAY-TV, we are sharing this story. Jackson Allard has family throughout the Southern Red River Valley. FARGO — Jackson Allard just turned 22 in November. He\'s a regular on Posh Boutique Fargo\'s daily Facebook Live auctions, a business his family runs. On Oct. 18, he went to the clinic with a stomach ache. His oxygen levels were too low, and he was diagnosed with influenza and double pneumonia. His oxygen levels continued to decline a week later, so he was intubated to give his lungs a chance to heal. There was still no improvement. As of Nov. 21, 2023, he’s on life support at the University of Minnesota. He\'s been on it for weeks. His last option for survival is a double lung transplant. WDAY News\' Michael McGurran has been in touch with his family, who are dealing with daily developments and taking time away from their work. They said along his medical journey, health professionals have raised concerns about a habit Allard and countless other people his age struggle with. An addiction to vaping. "Even though those vaping products do not contain tar, which was a big concern from cigarettes, they still have other airway irritants, potential carcinogens, and things that really can injure your lungs," said Dr. Stephanie Hanson, a pediatrician with Sanford Health. The damage vaping causes can make bouts of other lung-related diseases even more dangerous. "If you get an infection on top of that, pneumonia, influenza, you know, various viral infections, you really can get very sick in a hurry," Hanson said. For now, family and friends are stepping in to fill in the gaps at Posh Boutique, praying for just one piece of good news. A family friend is running a Go Fund Me on behalf of the Allard family. The fundraiser has a goal of $30,000, and has raised more than $18,000 as of Thursday, Nov. 30. A closer look at vaping’s effects on health, law enforcement, education and social environments will be included in “Our Community, Our Strength,” the 2024 Profile from Daily News and News Monitor. 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': "ADVERTISEMENT ADVERTISEMENT SIOUX FALLS – Gov. Kristi Noem’s personal life became very public over the weekend with salacious reports in London’s The Daily Mail and the New York Post . The stories suggest that South Dakota’s governor has been involved in a long-term extra-marital affair with Corey Lewandowski, a former campaign manager and current advisor for Donald Trump. Lewandowski also advises Noem and once served in an official capacity to the governor. The stories have circulated widely since publishing on Friday, Sept. 15. The revelations, the details of which have not been denied in the stories by the governor, rippled through political circles over the weekend. The story was first published online in the conservative-leaning Daily Mail, a London-based tabloid with one of the highest daily circulations in the U.K. The story includes a number of anonymous sources who say they witnessed Noem and Lewandowski together and detailed instances of the two traveling, often on private planes funded by donors, to political events around the country. ADVERTISEMENT The New York Post article referenced the Daily Mail's story and added five additional anonymous sources describing interactions between them at a hotel bar during the Conservative Political Action Conference in Orlando, Florida, in 2021, as well as Trump's resort at Mar-a-Lago in 2020. Noem, a loyal Trump supporter who recently endorsed the former president’s bid to retake the White House at a rally in Rapid City, is often mentioned as a potential running mate. She’s also been a much-sought after speaker for candidates and causes across the country, raising her national profile with appearances on national news networks. Those national ambitions have rankled many Republicans, particularly those who aren’t all-in for Trump, the current front-runner for the presidential nomination in 2024. But the tabloid headlines in London and New York City have taken that behind-the-scenes criticism to a new level. South Dakotans are less concerned with the private lives of their leaders than they are the day-to-day challenges of getting by, said one long-time political adviser and GOP donor. “As South Dakotans, we pay for these distractions,” the donor said. “Young families in Sioux Falls have been priced out of buying a beginner home, counties are broke and property taxes across the state are skyrocketing. People are hanging on by a financial thread and distractions aren’t going to help them.” Noem’s communications director, Ian Fury, declined to speak on the matter when contacted by Sioux Falls Live on Friday. On the record, most Republicans in the state choose their words carefully. ADVERTISEMENT Senate President Lee Schoenbeck said he would be the last to know what Gov. Noem does in her personal life, that he attends no meetings with her and rarely talks with her. “I think extremely highly of her family,” Schoenbeck said. “[Her husband] Bryon Noem is as good a person you would ever want to have for a friend, and I like her kids a lot, but I don’t have any dealings with her.” Rep. Greg Jamison of Sioux Falls said Noem seems more focused on national issues rather than traveling the state talking to people about their challenges and potential solutions. “Those kinds of things always seem to come out about people who are a rising political star,” Jamison said. “The Kristi Noem that I know doesn’t match any of those descriptions or accounts, but Kristi and I don’t chit chat either.” Other lawmakers simply don’t believe it’s true. “Those stories are tabloid garbage,” said House Majority Leader Rep. Will Mortenson of Pierre. “I don’t believe them and am not paying attention to them.” Spencer Gosch, who was Speaker of the House in 2022, said if the relationship between Noem and Lewandowski is a rumor, it’s one that’s been going on for a long time. “I haven’t seen anything to corroborate it. I couldn’t even speculate to its truth or not,” said Gosch, who’s from Mobridge. “Of course you hear things but you hear a lot of things in politics. You let a lot of it roll off your back.” ADVERTISEMENT Gosch was defeated in a Republican primary for a seat in the Senate by a candidate endorsed by the governor. Lewandowski was not a public figure during his time in Pierre, Gosch said. “I wouldn’t be able to point Corey Lewandowski out of a room. I’ve never known much about the guy and I never really cared to.” Jamison, who serves on the tax committee, said soaring property taxes are the biggest challenge facing South Dakota right now. Keeping people on a fixed income in their homes, and not having them priced out by a property tax bill they can’t pay, needs to be the focus. “Somebody said to me recently, ‘Wouldn't it be nice to go back to the governor being boring?’” ADVERTISEMENT"}]

things going on. Trust me. As someone whose job it is to write about what's happening in state an local government, there just aren't enough hours in the day for me to cover all the things I'd like to write or talk about. That being said, a new source for news in the state can't be a bad thing, right? The North Dakota Monitor is a new state-based iteration of a nonprofit news organization called the States Newsroom. They fund reporters in some 38 states who cover politics, courts, government and other matters. They don't charge for subscriptions, and they don't run ads. Donors fund their reporting. Is that a good thing or a bad thing? Amy Dalrymple, the former editor of the Bismarck Tribune who is now heading up the Monitor, joined this episode of Plain Talk to discuss it. She answered questions about what her organization will be covering, and criticism the States Newsroom organization has taken from media watchdogs like NewsGuard over their nonprofit model. Also, on this episode, co-host Ben Hanson and I discuss the NDGOP's hiring of Andrew Nyhus to be its new executive director and the most recent court ruling about North Dakota's legislative map. District Court Judge Peter Welte is refusing to move a December 22 deadline for lawmakers to introduce a new map. Will the Legislature have to rush into their second special session of this year? Or will an appeal to the 8th Circuit, at the very least, move the deadline? Casiotone for the Painfully Alone’s 2016 fan favorite “Cold White Christmas” to Advance Base’s latest Christmas single, “Christmas Steve.” There have been enough Advance Base and Casiotone for the Painfully Alone Christmas songs to necessitate a Christmas Mixtape (available as a free download from Advance Base’s Bandcamp). The album’s worth of songs that make up Christmas Mixtape don’t celebrate Christmas but merely acknowledge the emotional weight of the holiday season & its sometimes dreary realities. Over sparkling electric piano & warm electronic drones, Ashworth sings of lonely Midwesterners negotiating complicated family dynamics while trudging past storefront Christmas displays on their way to dead-end jobs. The songs are funny as often as they’re sad, but always full of the rich humanity that fans have come to expect from Ashworth’s bruised balladry. Every December, Owen Ashworth tours the Advance Base & Casiotone for the Painfully Alone Christmas Mixtape songs through different corners of the US and Canada. He performs his melancholic acknowledgements of Christmas to holiday lovers and haters alike. “As both Advance Base and Casiotone for the Painfully Alone, Ashworth has traversed America, carefully detailing the coldest Christmases imaginable ... Robert’s funeral service was held on Saturday, November 18, 2023, at the American Lutheran Church in Stanley, ND. Pastor Rebecca Mangelsdorf officiated. The funeral service was broadcast, you can view Robert’s service directly on his obituary page on the website www.springanstevenson.com. Springan Stevenson Funeral Home of Stanley was entrusted with arrangements and services. Friends may sign the online register and give their condolences at www.springanstevenson.com. Sydney “Syd” Craft, 86, of Stanley, ND, passed away on Sunday, November 12, 2023, surrounded by his loving family at the Mountrail County Bethel Home in Stanley, ND. Sydney’s funeral service was held on Friday, November 17, 2023, at the Knife River Lutheran Church in Stanley, ND. Pastor Rebecca Mangelsdorf and Intern Milo Mell officiated. There was a public visitation on Thursday, November 16 at the Springan Stevenson Funeral Home in Stanley, ND followed by a private family service. Sydney was laid to rest at the Knife River Lutheran Cemetery in Stanley, ND. The funeral service was broadcast, you can view Sydney’s service directly on his obituary page on the website www.springanstevenson.com. Springan Stevenson Funeral Home of Stanley was entrusted with arrangements and services. Friends may sign the online register and give their condolences at www.springanstevenson.com. Richard Alvin “Rick” Trulson, 71, of Idaho Falls, passed away on Monday, November 13, 2023, at his home. He was under the care of his loving family and Aspen Home Health and Hospice. A celebration of life will be held at 3 p.m. Saturday, November 25, 2023, at The Brickyard Event Center, 1025 Ammon Road, Ammon, ID. In lieu of flowers, the family suggests donations be made to the Idaho Food Bank at https://idahofoodbank.org/donate/. If you knew Rick, please share your favorite memory, photo, video, song, message, or story with his family at www.woodfuneralhome.com. Benjamin Fox, 36, of New Town, died Friday, November 17, 2023, at a medical center in Arizona. Mark “Cuz” Fretheim, 54, of Tioga, passed away unexpectedly in his home on November 16, 2023. Mark’s funeral service was held on Tuesday, November 21, 2023 at Bethlehem Lutheran Church in Ross, ND. Pastor Rebecca Mangelsdorf and Intern Milo Mell officiated. Mark was laid to rest at Rose Hill Cemetery in Ross, ND. Springan Stevenson Funeral Home of Stanley was entrusted with arrangements and services. Friends may sign the online register and give their condolences at www.springanstevenson.com. He succeeds succeeds Amy Wobbema, owner/publisher of the New Rockford Transcript and Foster County Independent, Carrington. Allison Olimb, editor-in-chief of the Walsh County Press in Park River, was elected first vice president of the association, and Alyssa Meier, associate publisher of NorDak Publishing, was elected for second vice president. Seibel is the Bismarck Tribune’s managing director. Continuing on the NDNA board are Matt Von Pinnon of The Forum of Fargo-Moorhead and Terry Schwartzenberger of the Napoleon Homestead. I used the trip as an opportunity to see how Minot measured up. I wanted to see how we compared to other places. I didn’t have a lot of time, so my stops were brief. Most were maybe an hour – just enough time to walk around, take some pictures, grab a cup of coffee, and form a first impression. It’s hard to get an honest sense of a place by looking at its McDonalds, so I made the downtowns my focus. I stopped eighteen times: Dawson, Eufaula, Montgomery, Tupelo, Conway, Fort Smith, Ponca City, McPherson, Lindsborg, Salina, Concordia, Hastings, Aurora, Grand Island, Broken Bow, Valentine, Pierre, and Mobridge. So how did Minot measure up? Better than I expected. We’re doing pretty well. There are more places behind us than ahead, but the margins are slim, and we are definitely still in the pack. The places that are ahead are really ahead; they’ve separated themselves and are far in front. So what separates them? All I have as evidence is what I saw and some ideas, but here goes: pride, focus, and polish. Those aren’t tangible things, they’re values. But when those values are expressed through actions and investment, the results translate into outcomes that can be felt. I don’t know how else to put it, but you just know when you’re in a place that has its act together. I think we’re on the verge of that in Minot. If you haven’t been downtown in a while and looked at and felt what’s happening, do it. Get out and walk around. Is it a wildly thriving environment? Not yet. There’s plenty of room for progress. But the energy is there; it’s unmistakable. Both private and public investment have gotten us where we are. The question is what’s next? Will we keep our foot on the gas? Or will we lose focus? Are we proud enough to keep investing in ourselves, or will we trust the cynics who say we can’t, it’s impossible, or we’ll never ‘be’? We’re going to find out this Monday. City Council will take up wayfinding and welcome signs as a potential investment in ourselves. These items have been long-identified as part of our improvement plan going back to the International Economic Development Council’s recommendations to the City in 2018. But five years is a long time, and every year that passes makes it easier for elected and city officials to say we’ve done enough. From what I saw on my trip across the country, we still have work to do. And what happens if we skip the polishing? In my cynical moments, that’s what I expect we’ll do; we’re good at almost doing things well. But I hope my cynical side is wrong. Or if negativity about our past is justified, I hope we break the trend. Because from what I saw driving across the country, the places that really have it together didn’t skip the polishing. They were all proud of their place, and they were happy to have me there. I know that for sure because they had all built beautiful welcome signs to tell me so. If you’re like me and want to see Minot’s recent progress continue, it might make sense to reach out to the City Council and let them know. with some nice corn, Jasmine Meyer watches from the combine while James operates the Brandt grain bagger bag corn. Jasmine rides in the combine with her mom, Jen Meyer, at left, as Jen combines. Jasmine Meyer in the combine with her mom, Jen, watching James operate the grain cart, while Jen cuts corn. WILTON, N.D. – The Meyers finished soybean harvest thanks to a string of sunny, warm days without rain – perfect harvesting weather. Following soybeans, they started preparing their combine and header for corn harvest. “The weather has just been beautiful this week. It is a little chilly and it has been a little windy, but as far as mid-October, it’s beautiful,” said Jen Meyer, who farms with her husband, James, and daughter, Jasmine. “We finished our soybeans and that was just fun trying to get that finished. There were some little repairs on the combine. You are using your combine for as long as you can, and little stuff is going and breaking down on the last 50 acres.” After cutting their soybeans, they augered them into empty air bins. They air dried their beans from 15 percent moisture down to 12.5-13 percent, and it was easy to air dry in the warm temperatures. The Meyers were mostly pleased with their soybean results. “All in all, I was pretty happy with it. It could have been a little better in some spots, but the weed pressure just took over in a couple of spots,” Jen said, noting there were some wet spots last year that they couldn’t get rid of in the fall due to the early snow, so those spots had more weeds that were underneath the soil. The Meyers did not want to leave the soybeans in the field any longer than they had to. “The beans will dry down in the field, but if they get too mature and then they hit a hot day, they’ll actually bust open their pods and the beans will fly out,” she said. They started combining corn on Oct. 21. Jen had to change the combine header to the corn header. “We have some corn ready to go, but we’ve got a new corn header and we knew it was going to rain, so we just kind of went fast,” she said. “It is supposed to rain and we just figured we’d get a couple of acres off.” Later, Jen added that the rain held off until about 2 p.m., so they were able to combine about 80 acres of corn. The Meyers purchased another corn header just for the year. Starting next year, they will be switching to a 22-inch corn planter. “We have a 30-inch row corn planter right now, and James wants to switch to a 22-inch planter next spring, so we actually had to buy this header just for this year,” Jen said. “I really like this header. It’s a great header. I love it. I wish he wanted to stay on 30-inch rows.” The Meyers filled up the rest of their empty bins with corn. They didn’t want to move to another bin site, which was farther away in a different area entirely, so they decided to utilize the Brandt bag loader and bag the corn. “For all the work that it would take to move to a different bin site, we are bagging our corn,” she said. They will haul their corn to the ethanol plant in Falkirk, N.D. The custom silage chopper was not able to make it out to their farm, so they had to hire a different custom chopper. James helped pack the silage pile and he understands silage because he used to work for a dairy farmer in Minnesota when he was going to college for business and gunsmithing. “The silage chopper came and James had to help pack the silage tight into the pile, which wasn’t a big deal, but it just took him away from doing other things,” Jen said. “We were a little worried that it wasn’t going to be high enough moisture, but they said about 50 percent moisture, so that’s good. It was enough to ferment and it has to be packed pretty tight so it ferments.” Jen said the gunsmithing degree has really helped James on the farm because he has used the tools for that trade to make a lot of the pieces of the parts that they use in farm machinery on the farm. Once it rains, the Meyers planned to switch from cutting corn to hauling hay bales home. Their cow/calf pairs are out grazing, and once the corn is harvested, Jen hopes to set up electric fence and let them graze the corn aftermath. She said they will probably bring the pairs to a pasture where they can be fed this winter. They will wean the calves in November. “We have to take some pairs home before November, and the majority of the cows will stay in pasture until it snows, then we will drive them home and feed everyone here,” she said. For next spring, the Meyers plan to grow durum, soybeans and corn, and they would like to raise something that would harvest early. “We like doing durum and then we might put in pinto beans, depending on the price. I’d like to go back to an earlier-harvesting crop, so maybe canola or peas. We haven’t done peas in a long time, but I like peas,” she said. Now that Jen has been in agriculture for more than a decade, farming has gotten into her blood and she loves it. “It would be really hard for me not to be my own boss. I just enjoy farming. There are a lot of long, hard days, but then there are a lot of really easy days, too. I don’t get to do a lot of stuff with Jasmine during harvest, but then in January, February and March, I do have the time to spend with her,” she said. Jasmine decided to join the 4-H chapter in Wilton. The Meyers are going to be busy off the farm during the fall, as well. Jen is participating in the Burleigh County Farmers Union meeting and the North Dakota Cooperative meeting. Jen and James will also go to CHS annual meeting in December, as well as the North Dakota Farmer’s Union annual meeting. Jen also has a North Dakota Soybean Council meeting in December, and they will both go to the Commodity Classic. Jen thanks all the readers that followed along with their operation this summer. Farm & Ranch Guide would like to sincerely thank the Meyer family for sharing their story with our readers this growing season. Thank you for all the reports and photos. We wish them the best of luck in the future. Get local news delivered to your inbox!
